04964nam a22005655i 9780822388807DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20082008ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223888077 a10.1515/97808223888072doi  a(DE-B1597)552097  a(OCoLC)1224278832  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aPOL0020002bisacsh04a307.1/412089980861532221 aGow, David D., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCountering Development :bIndigenous Modernity and the Moral Imagination /cDavid D. Gow. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2008] 4cÂ©2008  a1 online resource (315 p.) :b12 b&w photos, 1 map  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction: Beyond the Developmental Gaze -- t1 More Than an Engaged Fieldnote Collaboration, Dialogue, and Difference -- t2 Disaster and Diaspora Discourses of Development and Opportunity -- t3 Development Planning Slaves of Modernity or Agents of Change? -- t4 Local Knowledge, Different Dreams Planning for the Next Generation -- t5 The Nasa of the North and the Tensions of Modernity -- t6 Beyond Development The Continuing Struggle for Peace, Justice, and Inclusion -- tConclusion: Countering Development Indigenous Modernity and the Moral Imagination -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCauca, located in southwestern Colombia and home to the largest indigenous population in the country, is renowned as a site of indigenous mobilization. In 1994, following a destructive earthquake, many families in Cauca were forced to leave their communities of origin and relocate to other areas within the province where the state provided them with land and housing. Noting that disasters offer communities the opportunity to remake themselves and their priorities, David D. Gow examines how three different communities established after the earthquake wrestled with conflicting visions of development. He shows how they each countered traditional notions of development by moving beyond a myopic obsession with poverty alleviation to demand that Colombia become more inclusive and treat all of its people as citizens with full rights and responsibilities.Through ethnographic fieldwork conducted annually in Cauca from 1995 through 2002, Gow compares the development plans of the three communities, looking at both the planning processes and the plans themselves. In so doing, he demonstrates that there is no single indigenous approach to development and modernity. He describes differences in how each community defined and employed the concept of culture, how they connected a concern with culture to economic and political reconstruction, and how they sought to assert their own priorities while engaging with the existing development resources at their disposal. Ultimately, Gow argues that the moral vision advanced by the indigenous movement, combined with the growing importance attached to human rights, offers a fruitful way to think about development: less as a process of integration into a rigidly defined modernity than as a critical modernity based on a radical politics of inclusive citizenship.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aEconomic developmentzColombiazCauca (Dept.). 0aIndians of South AmericaxCommercezColombiazCauca (Dept.). 0aIndians of South AmericazColombiazCauca (Dept.)xEconomic conditions. 0aIndians of South AmericazColombiazCauca (Dept.)xGovernment relations. 0aSustainable developmentzColombiazCauca (Dept.). 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / City Planning & Urban Development.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Backlist